---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';

const byomExample = `const client = IdrClient.forService('ollama');
await client.connect({ host: userProvidedHost });
await client.fetch('/api/chat', { method: 'POST', body: … });`;

const browserPattern = `import { IdrClient } from '@idrto/idr_browser_sdk';

// Dev-time: pick service (maps to port on target)
const client = IdrClient.forService('ollama'); // → 11434

// Runtime: user auth + target host only
await client.ensureSession({ interactive: true, mount: authElement });
await client.connect({ host: userEnteredHost });
const res = await client.fetch('/api/tags');`;

const dartExample = `import 'package:idr_dart_sdk/idr_dart_sdk.dart';

final client = await IdrClient.open(IdrConfig(
  apiBaseUrl: 'https://idr.to',
  stateDir: stateDir,
  library: DefaultIdrNativeLibrary(libraryPath: nativeLibPath),
));

await client.loginWithPassword(email: 'user@example.com', password: '…');
await client.startAgent(mode: IdrAgentMode.target);
await client.connect('idrto:laptop~user-40example.com/ssh');`;
---

<Layout title="ISVs & SDKs — idr.to">
  <Header slot="header" />
  <Footer slot="footer" />

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">For software vendors</p>
      <h1>Embed idr.to in your apps</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Ship products that connect to customer-owned edge hardware — GPU boxes, factory gateways, on-prem APIs —
        without VPNs or static IPs. ISVs hardcode the service; end-users supply target host and credentials via SDK UI.
      </p>

      <h2>Bring Your Own Machine (BYOM)</h2>
      <p>
        The primary ISV pattern for on-device AI: your users run workloads on <strong>their own hardware</strong>
        (Mac Mini, Linux GPU box, office PC) — you never host the model. They install Ollama (or similar) and an
        idr.to target agent; your web app connects with a hardcoded service. Register a host to form a
        <strong>Host-Identity</strong> (<code>host~entity-id</code>) with a globally routable <strong>FQHN</strong>;
        each machine has its own <strong>Device-ID</strong> for routing.
      </p>
      <pre><code>{byomExample}</code></pre>

      <h3>Detailed case study: Ollama on M4 Mac Mini</h3>
      <p>
        The full BYOM walkthrough covers Host-Identity registration, FQHN formats, CLI and Browser SDK access,
        streaming <code>/api/chat</code>, RAG with embeddings, access keys for contractors, and fallback paths
        (TURN / HTTPS relay). Inference and model weights never leave the customer's edge box.
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>1</td><td>Customer registers device → <strong>Device-ID</strong> (routing address)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2</td><td><code>idr host register gpu-a.us-east</code> → <strong>Host-Identity</strong> + FQHN</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3</td><td>Ollama on <code>127.0.0.1:11434</code>; agent forwards tunnel OPEN</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4</td><td>ISV app: <code>IdrClient.forService('ollama')</code> + user enters host</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5</td><td>P2P WebRTC carries HTTP to Ollama — idr.to never sees prompts</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/case-study/ollama">Full Ollama BYOM case study →</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/case-study/nginx">Web app case study (nginx + Node.js)</a>
      </p>

      <h2>Bundle size</h2>
      <p>
        Measured from production build (<code>npm run build</code>, tsup minify + gzip). WebRTC is built into the browser — not included in these figures.
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Artifact</th><th>Minified</th><th>Gzip</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>ESM entry (<code>dist/index.js</code>)</td><td>~37 KB</td><td><strong>~11 KB</strong></td></tr>
            <tr><td>CJS entry (<code>dist/index.cjs</code>)</td><td>~43 KB</td><td>~13 KB</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Auth panel chunk (lazy)</td><td>~4 KB</td><td>~1.3 KB</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="callout">
        Typical SPA impact: <strong>~11–12 KB gzip</strong> for core SDK + auth UI when users sign in. No native binaries in the browser bundle.
      </p>

      <h2>Browser SDK</h2>
      <p><strong>Package:</strong> <code>@idrto/idr_browser_sdk</code> — WebRTC + HTTP-over-tunnel for web apps.</p>

      <h3>Integration pattern</h3>
      <pre><code>{browserPattern}</code></pre>

      <h3>Rules for ISVs</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Do</th><th>Don't</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Use <code>mountAuthPanel()</code> / <code>&lt;idr-auth-panel&gt;</code></td><td>Build your own access-key input</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Let users enter <code>host.entity.idr</code> or idrto URI</td><td>POST tokens to your backend</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Hardcode service name at build time</td><td>Pass <code>accessKey</code> to <code>connect()</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>CSP: <code>connect-src https://idr.to wss://idr.to</code></td><td>Override platform URLs</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3>Framework examples</h3>
      <p>Vanilla, React, Vue, Svelte, and Angular Vite starters ship in the <a href="https://github.com/idrto/idr_browser_sdk">idr_browser_sdk</a> repo.</p>

      <h3>Auth options</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Account login</strong> — <code>POST /v1/auth/browser/login</code> (OIDC-style session)</li>
        <li><strong>Access keys</strong> — owner-issued <code>idr_ak_…</code> for delegates; exchanged client-side only</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Dart SDK (mobile &amp; desktop)</h2>
      <p>
        Native agent on <strong>Linux, macOS, Windows, Android, and iOS</strong> via FFI.
        <strong>Package:</strong> <code>idr_dart_sdk</code>.
      </p>
      <pre><code>{dartExample}</code></pre>

      <h3>Platform artifacts</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Platform</th><th>Native library</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Linux / Android</td><td><code>libidr_sdk.so</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>macOS</td><td><code>libidr_sdk.dylib</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Windows</td><td><code>idr_sdk.dll</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td>iOS</td><td>static <code>libidr_sdk.a</code></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>Build from the <a href="https://github.com/idrto/agent/tree/main/crates/idr-ffi">client idr-ffi crate</a> and ship the library with your app.</p>

      <h2>Other embed options</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>C / C++ FFI</strong> — same <code>libidr_sdk</code> for native integrations</li>
        <li><strong>Rust crate</strong> — full agent in-process for appliances</li>
        <li><strong>CLI subprocess</strong> — wrap <code>idr connect</code> for quick prototypes</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>White-label / multi-tenant</h2>
      <p>
        ISVs can point SDKs at dedicated tenants (<code>{'{slug}'}.t.idr.to</code> or custom CNAME).
        Bake <code>apiBaseUrl</code> at build time; signaling URL is derived automatically.
      </p>

      <h2>Get started</h2>
      <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/evaluate">30-day evaluation</a>
      <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="https://github.com/idrto/idr_browser_sdk/blob/main/docs/ISV_GUIDE.md">Full ISV guide (GitHub)</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  h1 { font-size: 2.25rem; margin: 0 0 1rem; }
  h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem; }
  h3 { font-size: 1.125rem; margin: 1.25rem 0 0.75rem; }
  ul { color: var(--text-muted); }
</style>
